\par
\pard\fi720 B\b0\fs36 ehavioral Science, the FBI section that deals with serial murder, is on the bottom floor of the Acad\f1\-\f5 emy building at Quantico, half-buried in the earth. Clarice Starling reached it flushed after a fast walk from Hogan's Alley on the firing range. She had grass in her hair and grass stains on her FBI Academy windbreaker from diving to the ground under fire in an arrest prob\f1\-\f5 lem on the range.\par
\pard\fi720\tx201 No one was in the outer office, so she fluffed briefly by her reflection in the glass doors. She knew she could look all right without primping. Her hands smelled of gunsmoke, but there was no time to wash--- Section Chief Crawford's summons had said now.\par
She found Jack Crawford alone in the cluttered suite of offices. He was standing at someone else's desk talk\f1\-\f5 ing on the telephone and she had a chance to look him over for the first time in a year. What she saw disturbed her.\par
Normally, Crawford looked like a fit, middle-aged engineer who might have paid his way through college playing baseball--- a crafty catcher, tough when he blocked the plate. Now he was thin, his shirt collar was too big, and he had dark puffs under his reddened eyes. Everyone who could read the papers knew Behavioral Science section was catching hell. Starling hoped Craw\f1\-\f5 ford wasn't on the juice. That seemed most unlikely here.\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 Crawford ended his telephone conversation with a sharp "No." He took her file from under his arm and opened it.\par
\pard\fi720\tx215\tx412 "Starling, Clarice M., good morning," he said.\par
\pard\fi720\tx221\tx418 "Hello." Her smile was only polite.\par
\pard\fi720\tx216\tx413 "Nothing's wrong. I hope the call didn't spook you."\par
\pard\fi720\tx221\tx418 "No." \i\f4 Not totally true,\f5  \i0 Starling thought.\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 "Your instructors tell me you're doing well, top quarter of the class."\par
\pard\fi720\tx215\tx412 "I hope so, they haven't posted anything."\par
"I ask them from time to time."\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 That surprised Starling; she had written Crawford off as a two-faced recruiting sergeant son of a bitch.\par
She had met Special Agent Crawford when he was a guest lecturer at the University of Virginia. The qual\f1\-\f5 ity of his criminology seminars was a factor in her coming to the Bureau. She wrote him a note when she qualified for the Academy, but he never replied, and for the three months she had been a trainee at Quantico, he had ignored her.\par
Starling came from people who do not ask for favors or press for friendship, but she was puzzled and regret\f1\-\f5 ful at Crawford's behavior. Now, in his presence, she liked him again, she was sorry to note.\par
Clearly something was wrong with him. There was a peculiar cleverness in Crawford, aside from his intel\f1\-\f5 ligence, and Starling had first noticed it in his color sense and the textures of his clothing, even within the FBI-clone standards of agent dress. Now he was neat but drab, as though he were molting.\par
"A job came up and I thought about you," he said. "It's not really a job, it's more of an interesting errand. Push Berry's stuff off that chair and sit down. You put down here that you want to come directly to Behav\f1\-\f5 ioral Science when you get through with the Acad\f1\-\f5 emy."\par
\pard\fi720\tx210 "I do."\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 "You have a lot of forensics, but no law enforcement background. We look for six years, minimum."\par
\pard\fi720\tx219\tx416 "My father was a marshal, I know the life."\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 Crawford smiled a little. "What you \i\f4 do \i0\f5 have is a double major in psychology and criminology, and how many summers working in a mental health center--- \f1\-\f5 two?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx232 "Two."\par
"Your counselor's license, is it current?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 "It's good for two more years. I got it before you had the seminar at UVA--- before I decided to do this."\par
\pard\fi720\tx237\tx434 "You got stuck in the hiring freeze."\par
\pard\fi720\tx197 Starling nodded. "I was lucky though--- I found out in time to qualify as a Forensic Fellow. Then I could work in the lab until the Academy had an opening."\par
"You wrote to me about coming here, didn't you, and I don't think I answered--- I know I didn't. I should have."\par
\pard\fi720\tx249\tx446 "You've had plenty else to do."\par
"Do you know about VI-CAP?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx51\tx248 "I know it's the Violent Criminal Apprehension Pro\f1\-\f5 gram. The \i\f4 Law Enforcement Bulletin \i0\f5 says you're working on a database, but you aren't operational yet."\par
\pard\fi720\tx56\tx253 Crawford nodded. "We've developed a question\f1\-\f5 naire. It applies to all the known serial murderers in modern times." He handed her a thick sheaf of papers in a flimsy binding. "There's a section for investigators, and one for surviving victims, if any. The blue is for the killer to answer if he will, and the pink is a series of questions an examiner asks the killer, getting his reactions as well as his answers. It's a lot of paperwork."\par
\pard\fi720\tx266\tx463 Paperwork. Clarice Starling's self-interest snuffled ahead like a keen beagle. She smelled a job offer com\f1\-\f5 ing--- probably the drudgery of feeding raw data into a new computer system. It was tempting to get into Be\f1\-\f5 havioral Science in any capacity she could, but she knew what happens to a woman if she's ever pegged as a secretary--- it sticks until the end of time. A choice was coming, and she wanted to choose well.\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 Crawford was waiting for something--- he must have asked her a question. Starling had to scramble to recall it.\par
"What tests have you given? Minnesota Multi\f1\-\f5 phasic, ever? Rorschach?"\par
"Yes, MMPI, never Rorschach," she said. "I've done Thematic Apperception and I've given children Bender-Gestalt."\par
\pard\fi720\tx225\tx427 "Do you spook easily, Starling?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx237\tx439 "Not yet."\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "See, we've tried to interview and examine all the thirty-two known serial murderers we have in custody, to build up a database for psychological profiling is unsolved cases. Most of them went along with it--- I think they're driven to show off, a lot of them. Twenty\f1\-\f5 -seven were willing to cooperate. Four on death row with appeals pending clammed up, understandably. But the one we want the most, we haven't been able to get. I want you to go after him tomorrow in the asy\f1\-\f5 lum."\par
Clarice Starling felt a glad knocking in her chest and some apprehension too.\par
\pard\fi720\tx232\tx434 "Who's the subject?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx232\tqr\tx4835 "The psychiatrist--- Dr. Hannibal Lecter," Crawford said.\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 A brief silence follows the name, always, in any civi\f1\-\f5 lized gathering.\par
Starling looked at Crawford steadily, but she was too still. "Hannibal the Cannibal," she said.\par
\pard\fi720\tx225\tx427 "Yes."\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "Yes, well--- Okay, right. I'm glad of the chance, but you have to know I'm wondering--- why me?"\par
"Mainly because you're available," Crawford said. "I don't expect him to cooperate. He's already refused, but it was through an intermediary--- the director of the hospital. I have to be able to say our qualified examiner went to him and asked him personally. There are rea\f1\-\f5 sons that don't concern you. I don't have anybody left in this section to do it."\par
\pard\fi720 ' "You're jammed--- Buffalo Bill--- and the things in Nevada," Starling said.\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "You got it. It's the old story--- not enough warm bodies."\par
"You said tomorrow--- you're in a hurry. Any bearing on a current case?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx230\tx432 "No. I wish there were."\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "If he balks on me, do you still want a psychological evaluation?"\par
"No. I'm waist-deep in inaccessible-patient evalua\f1\-\f5 tions of Dr. Lecter and they're all different."\par
Crawford shook two vitamin C tablets into his palm, and mixed an Alka-Seltzer at the water cooler to wash them down. "It's ridiculous, you know; Lecter's a psy\f1\-\f5 chiatrist and he writes for the psychiatric journals him\f1\-\f5 self--- extraordinary stuff--- but it's never about his own little anomalies. He pretended to go along with the hospital director, Chilton, once in some tests--- sitting around with a blood-pressure cuff on his penis, looking at wreck pictures--- then Lecter published first what he'd learned about Chilton and made a fool out of him. He responds to serious correspondence from psychiat\f1\-\f5 ric students in fields unrelated to his case, and that's all he does. If he won't talk to you, I just want straight reporting. How does he look, how does his cell look, what's he doing. Local color, so to speak. Watch out for the press going in and coming out. Not the real press, the supermarket press. They love Lecter even better than Prince Andrew."\par
"Didn't a sleazo magazine offer him fifty thousand dollars for some recipes? I seem to remember that," Starling said.\par
Crawford nodded. "I'm pretty sure the \i\f4 National Tattler\f5  \i0 has bought somebody inside the hospital and they may know you're coming after I make the appointment."\par
Crawford leaned forward until he faced her at a dis\f1\-\f5 tance of two feet. She watched his half-glasses blur the bags under his eyes. He had gargled recently with Listerine.\par
"Now. I want your full attention, Starling. Are you listening to me?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx192\tx394 "Yes sir."\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "Be very careful with Hannibal Lecter. Dr. Chilton, the head of the mental hospital, will go over the physi\f1\-\f5 cal procedure you use to deal with him. Don't deviate from it. \i\f4 Do not deviate from it one iota for any reason.\f5  \i0 If Lecter talks to you at all, he'll just be trying to find out about you. It's the kind of curiosity that makes a snake look in a bird's nest. We both know you have to back-and-\f1\-\f5 forth a little in interviews, but you tell him no specifics about yourself. You don't want any of your personal facts in his head. You know what he did to Will Gra\f1\-\f5 ham."\par
\pard\fi720\tx202\tx404 "I read about it when it happened."\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "He gutted Will with a linoleum knife when Will caught up with him. It's a wonder Will didn't die. Re\f1\-\f5 member the Red Dragon? Lecter turned Francis Dolar\f1\-\f5 hyde onto Will and his family. Will's face looks like damn Picasso drew him, thanks to Lecter. He tore a nurse up in the asylum. Do your job, just don't ever forget what he is."\par
\pard\fi720\tx203\tx405 "And what's that? Do you know?"\par
\pard\fi720\tx202 "I know he's a monster. Beyond that, nobody can say for sure. Maybe you'll find out; I didn't pick you out of a hat, Starling. You asked me a couple of interesting questions when I was at UVA. The Director will see your own report over your signature--- if it's clear and tight and organized. I decide that. And I \i\f4 will \i0\f5 have it by 0900 Sunday. Okay, Starling, carry on in the prescribed manner."\par
Crawford smiled at her, but his eyes were dead.\par
